-- Canadian First-Quarter Company Profits Decline 1.2% on Insurers
-- B y   T h e o p h i l o s   A r g i t i s
-- 2013-05-28T12:30:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-28/canadian-first-quarter-company-profits-decline-1-2-on-insurers.html
Canadian corporate profits decreased
1.2 percent in the first quarter, led by declines by insurance
companies.  Operating profits fell to C$74 billion ($71.7 billion) in
the January-March period from C$74.9 billion in the previous
quarter, Statistics Canada said today in Ottawa. Profits were
down 3.3 percent from the first quarter of 2012.  Fourteen of 22 industries reported lower earnings in the
quarter, with insurers recording a 16 percent drop to C$3.9
billion, Statistics Canada said. Profits of all financial
companies declined 4.7 percent to C$20.4 billion.  Earnings for all non-financial companies rose 0.3 percent
to C$53.6 billion in the first quarter, according to the report.
Profits for the oil and gas industry recovered in the first
quarter after six consecutive quarterly declines, gaining 28.3
percent to C$1.7 billion, while retail trade profit increased
1.7 percent to C$4.1 billion. Manufacturing profits dropped 1.0
percent to C$12.1 billion.  To contact the reporter on this story:
